resonated, not only among academics, but also in the popular press. It delves into the historical roots of postmodern and poststructuralist, while also subjecting more recent post-constructions (posthumanist, postfeminist) to critical scrutiny.This study is the first to offer a comprehensive history of post-concepts. In tracing how these concepts found their way into a broad range of genres and disciplines, Post-everything contributes to a rapprochement between the history of the humanities and the history of the social sciences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh  aConceptual history.  aHistoricism.  aIntellectual history.  aPerformativity.  aPost-colonialism.  aPost-concepts.  aPost-truth.  aPostmodernism.  aPrefixes.  aTransnationalism.1 aBackhouse, Roger E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaring, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertens, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrick, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaston, K. Healan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenz, Stéphanie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJansen, Yolande, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeeuwenkamp, Jasmijn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Herman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaul, Herman, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSartori, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https